<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-008-089 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 577 020</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Nov 25 1991 v10 n24 p57(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Weather Service radar system finally makes debut. (United States.andO;National Weather Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smith, James M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National Weather Service (NWS) and the National Oceanic andAtmospheric Administration (NOAA) have introduced theminicomputer-based Next Generation Weather Radar (NEXRAD) at theNational Washington/Sterling (VA) Weather Forecast Office inVirginia.andP;  NEXRAD is a powerful Doppler radar system.andP;  NEXRAD,which was developed by Unisys Corp, has been criticized for beingover its budget and behind on its schedule.andP;  NOAA even threatenedto cancel the NEXRAD contract, but a compromise was worked out,and the NWS and NOAA seem pleased with the system that is finallydelivered.andP;  When it is completely installed, the $800 millionNEXRAD system will be in use at 115 NOAA sites as well as at 30Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) locations and 30 Departmentof Defense (DOD) bases.andP;  The system is expected to bring greatlyincreased forecasting capabilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Weather ServiceRadar SystemsMeteorologyGovernment Contracts.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>